            <!-- FAQ Section -->
            <div class="blog-faq">
                <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3>How are quartz countertops made?</h3>
                    <p>Quartz countertops are manufactured by combining approximately 90 to 95 percent ground natural quartz crystals with 5 to 10 percent polymer resins, pigments, and binding agents. The mixture is poured into a mold and compacted under intense vibration and pressure using a process called Breton vibration compaction. The slabs are then cured at high temperatures, cooled, calibrated to a uniform thickness, and polished to their final finish. The entire process transforms raw quartz mineral into a dense, non-porous engineered stone surface.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3>What are the pros and cons of quartz countertops?</h3>
                    <p>The main pros of quartz countertops include a non-porous surface that never needs sealing, excellent stain resistance, a huge selection of colors and patterns, consistent appearance across slabs, exceptional durability, a hygienic surface that resists bacteria, and low maintenance requiring just soap and water. The cons include moderate heat resistance (can be damaged above 300 degrees Fahrenheit), susceptibility to yellowing with prolonged UV exposure, incompatibility with harsh chemicals like bleach, and the fact that it is an engineered product rather than natural stone.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3>Are quartz countertops heat resistant?</h3>
                    <p>Quartz countertops are moderately heat resistant but not heatproof. They can typically withstand temperatures up to about 300 degrees Fahrenheit without damage. However, placing a hot pan, baking sheet, or crockpot directly from the stove or oven onto a quartz surface can cause the polymer resins to discolor, crack, or scorch. Always use trivets, hot pads, or cutting boards under hot cookware to protect your quartz countertops.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3>Do quartz countertops stain?</h3>
                    <p>Quartz countertops are highly stain-resistant but not completely stain-proof. Because quartz is non-porous, most common kitchen substances like wine, coffee, juice, and oil sit on the surface and wipe away easily. However, leaving strongly pigmented substances like turmeric, permanent marker, or hair dye on the surface for extended periods can cause discoloration. Harsh chemicals like bleach or oven cleaner can also damage the resin and cause permanent marks. The key is to wipe up spills promptly.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3>Do quartz countertops need to be sealed?</h3>
                    <p>No, quartz countertops never need to be sealed. This is one of their biggest advantages over natural stone options like granite and marble. Because quartz is an engineered surface with polymer resins filling every gap between the quartz crystals, the result is a completely non-porous material. Liquids, bacteria, and stains cannot penetrate the surface. You will never need to buy sealant or schedule professional sealing, which saves both time and money over the life of the countertop.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3>How much do quartz countertops cost?</h3>
                    <p>In South Florida, quartz countertops typically cost between $50 and $120 per square foot fully installed. Entry-level options from brands like MSI start around $50 to $65 per square foot. Mid-range quartz from Silestone or Caesarstone runs $65 to $90 per square foot. Premium quartz from Cambria or designer collections costs $90 to $120 or more per square foot. For a typical 40 square foot kitchen countertop project, expect to invest between $2,000 and $4,800 installed.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3>How long do quartz countertops last?</h3>
                    <p>Quartz countertops are designed to last a lifetime with proper care. Most manufacturers offer warranties ranging from 15 years to a full lifetime, with brands like Cambria providing a transferable lifetime warranty. Under normal residential use, quartz countertops will easily last 25 years or more without showing significant wear. They will not fade, crack, or degrade as long as you protect them from extreme heat, prolonged UV exposure, and harsh chemical cleaners.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3>Can quartz countertops be used outdoors in South Florida?</h3>
                    <p>Quartz countertops are generally not recommended for uncovered outdoor installations in South Florida. Prolonged exposure to the intense Florida UV rays can cause the polymer resins to yellow or discolor over time. If you want quartz in a covered outdoor kitchen or lanai where direct sunlight is minimal, it can work well. For fully exposed outdoor countertops, natural stone options like quartzite or granite are better choices because they are UV-stable and will not discolor in sunlight.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3>What is the difference between quartz and quartzite countertops?</h3>
                    <p>Quartz and quartzite are completely different materials despite their similar names. Quartz countertops are engineered in a factory from ground quartz crystals mixed with polymer resins. Quartzite is a 100 percent natural metamorphic rock quarried from the earth. Quartz is non-porous and never needs sealing, while quartzite requires periodic sealing. Quartz offers consistent patterns across slabs while every quartzite slab is unique. Quartzite has better heat and UV resistance, but quartz requires far less maintenance.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <h3>What edge profiles are available for quartz countertops?</h3>
                    <p>Quartz countertops can be fabricated with virtually any edge profile. The most popular options include straight or eased edges for a clean modern look, beveled edges for subtle sophistication, half bullnose and full bullnose for rounded comfort, ogee edges for traditional elegance, and mitered or waterfall edges for dramatic contemporary designs. The best edge profile depends on your kitchen style, countertop thickness, and personal preference. Your fabricator can show you samples of each profile to help you choose.</p>
                </div>
